    en: "A Rochester business discovered that a recently-departed senior employee had taken customer lists and was soliciting customers on behalf of a competitor — in violation of a post-employment non-compete agreement. The business filed suit in Monroe County Supreme Court and simultaneously moved for a TRO under CPLR 6313 to stop continued solicitation pending a PI hearing. Supporting affidavits described the unique customer relationships (irreparable harm), documented the non-compete (likelihood of success), and showed the former employee could continue operating in the business's non-customer territory without substantial hardship (balance of equities). The TRO issued same-day on notice to opposing counsel; the PI hearing was scheduled 12 days later. At the PI hearing the court found all three prongs met. A preliminary injunction issued for the 12-month non-compete period, with a $50,000 bond required. The competitor ultimately settled the underlying action to avoid protracted litigation."
